ğŸ­ BREAKING: MADURO GETS THE ULTIMATE SURPRISE PARTY Y&rsquo;all, the Americans just Uber-kidnapped an entire president. Not even DoorDash is that efficient.
What Happened: Trump sent the boys to Venezuela like it was a Black Friday sale at Courts. Operation resulted in NicolÃ¡s Maduro getting the express trip to New York he DEFINITELY didn&rsquo;t book on Travelocity.
Guyana&rsquo;s Response: President Ali is doing that Caribbean thing where you&rsquo;re simultaneously thrilled, terrified, and trying not to laugh. He commended Trump which is like thanking the bouncer for removing your drunk ex from the party.
Stabroek News: adjusts intellectual glasses &ldquo;We must consider the geopolitical implications&hellip;&rdquo;
Kaieteur News: &ldquo;MADURO GRABBED! WE BEEN TELLING Y&rsquo;ALL!&rdquo;
Chronicle: &ldquo;President Ali Says Things. Government Does Stuff. Everything Fine.&rdquo;
Guyana Times: &ldquo;Anyway, here&rsquo;s a story about motorsports and a beauty pageant.&rdquo;
Real Talk: Guyana just watched its annoying neighbor get arrested on COPS: International Edition. Live. In real time. While the whole Caribbean group chat was going absolutely wild.
The Awkward Part: Now Guyana has to pretend they&rsquo;re not THRILLED about this. Because diplomacy. And international relations. And the fact that they share a border with a country that just got regime-changed via air strike.
ğŸ’° THE MOHAMEDS: AMERICA&rsquo;S MOST WANTED This father-son duo is having the kind of week that makes you reconsider all your life choices.
The Situation: The Mohameds are fighting extradition to Florida harder than your auntie fights for the last piece of black cake at Christmas. Their legal strategy appears to be &ldquo;The Mohameds are NOT going anywhere!&rdquo; which is NOT how extradition treaties work.
Their Lawyers Said: &ldquo;We are confident this case will be dismissed.&rdquo;
The Court Said: &ldquo;No.&rdquo;
Their Lawyers Said: &ldquo;Well, we&rsquo;re appealing.&rdquo;
Everyone Else: &ldquo;Of course you are.&rdquo;
Kaieteur&rsquo;s Coverage: They&rsquo;ve written more about the Mohameds than the Mohameds&rsquo; mothers did in baby books. At this point, Kaieteur News could publish a Mohameds encyclopedia.
Best Headlines This Week:
&ldquo;The Mohameds are not going anywhere&rdquo; (Monday) &ldquo;Mohamed extradition hearing continues&rdquo; (Tuesday) &ldquo;Mohameds file appeal&rdquo; (Wednesday) &ldquo;Court rejects Mohamed appeal&rdquo; (Thursday) The Pattern: Court says yes, Lawyers say no, Appeal filed, Repeat. They&rsquo;re currently on loop 4.
Florida&rsquo;s Patience Level: Approaching zero. The US Attorney&rsquo;s office has started sending strongly worded letters, which in legal terms is like your mom using your full name.
ğŸ›£ï¸ HEROES HIGHWAY: A LOVE STORY GONE WRONG December 2023: Government unveils shiny new concrete highway
January 2025: Ministry announces asphalt overlay project
Let&rsquo;s Do The Math: That&rsquo;s 13 months. The highway lasted about as long as a New Year&rsquo;s resolution.
Translation: They built a highway with concrete. Premium concrete. It lasted barely over a year. Now they want to cover it with asphalt.
This is like:
Buying a Tesla and gluing a bicycle on top Ordering premium steak and covering it with ketchup Building a mansion and putting up wallpaper to hide the cracks Stabroek News (Being Polite): &ldquo;Questions have been raised about whether sound decisions are being made&hellip;&rdquo;
Us (Not Being Polite): Y&rsquo;ALL BUILT A HIGHWAY WRONG.
The Excuse: &ldquo;The concrete surface requires an asphalt overlay for optimal performance.&rdquo;
The Translation: &ldquo;We messed up but we&rsquo;re using technical words to make it sound intentional.&rdquo;
What Actually Happened: Someone made a decision. That decision was wrong. That wrongness cost millions. Now another decision will cost more millions to fix the first wrong decision.
Engineering 101: Concrete highways should last 20-30 years. Heroes Highway speedran that timeline like it was going for a world record.
ğŸ“± DIGITAL SCHOOL: WHEN ZOOM FINALLY CAME TO GUYANA The Ministry of Education is THRILLED to announce that students successfully&hellip; logged into Zoom.
Let That Sink In: The achievement isn&rsquo;t the lesson. The achievement isn&rsquo;t the teaching. The achievement is that THE INTERNET DIDN&rsquo;T CRASH.
Participating Schools: Dora Secondary, St. Cuthbert&rsquo;s Secondary, Kwakwani Secondary, Linden Foundation Secondary, Anna Regina Secondary.
The Real Achievement: &ldquo;Guyana Internet Works For Thing: Nation Shocked&rdquo;
Parent&rsquo;s Perspective: &ldquo;So my data plan is now a school supply?&rdquo;
Teacher&rsquo;s Perspective: &ldquo;I spent 45 minutes troubleshooting connectivity and 10 minutes teaching.&rdquo;
Government&rsquo;s Perspective: &ldquo;DIGITAL TRANSFORMATION! PROGRESS!&rdquo;
Reality Check: Other countries have been doing this since 2020. We&rsquo;re celebrating in 2026 that we successfully used Zoom. The app your grandmother figured out during COVID.
ğŸŒ¾ RICE FARMERS GET 2.1 BILLION Agriculture Minister Mustapha is touring the country handing out checks like Oprah&rsquo;s Guyanese cousin.
The Official Story: &ldquo;Government assistance initiative&rdquo;
The Real Story: &ldquo;Remember when y&rsquo;all flooded twice? Here&rsquo;s some money. Sorry about that.&rdquo;
Black Bush Polder Residents: &ldquo;Our crops are still underwater but okay, thanks.&rdquo;
May 2024: Flooding
December 2024: More flooding
January 2025: Money for the flooding
The Cycle:
Build drainage systems Don&rsquo;t maintain them Flooding happens Act surprised Give out money Repeat next year What Farmers Actually Need: Working drainage, flood prevention, infrastructure maintenance, maybe some oil money?
What Farmers Got: Checks after damage is done, photo op with minister, promises of improvement.
